TY  - JOUR
AU  - Anderson, Patricia M.
T1  - Linear Adjustment Costs and Seasonal Labor Demand: Evidence from Retail Trade Firms*
PY  - 1993
Y1  - 1993/11/01
DO  - 10.2307/2118458
JO  - The Quarterly Journal of Economics
JA  - Q J Econ
VL  - 108
IS  - 4
SP  - 1015
EP  - 1042
SN  - 0033-5533
AB  - Standard models of dynamic labor demand rely on the presence of adjustment costs to explain the observed smoothness in employment patterns, although the costs are often difficult to quantify. The experience rating feature of the U. S. Unemployment Insurance (UI) system provides a measurable linear cost of adjustment. Using a unique data set with administrative data on over 8000 firms, I estimate the effect of a UI-induced linear adjustment cost on seasonal labor demand in retail trade. I find strong support for the large role of adjustment costs in reducing the employment response of firms to seasonal fluctuations in demand.
Y2  - 3/25/2024
UR  - https://doi.org/10.2307/2118458
ER  - 



